I was also expecting corn tortillas, which I did not get, or at least they didn’t taste like corn.  The chips & guac were what I had hoped to be the saving grace, but those disappointed me as well. The chips tasted store bought and the guac was watery with almost no avocado flavor.  If you’re ordering tacos, try another place, I certainly will be in the future.

Tacos El Chilango is a small place for simple but tasty tacos. Beyond a range of four meat-based and four vegetarian options, the menu is spartan, including store-bought chips with homemade guacamole and two types of homemade salsa. The best taco on the menu is with chorizo, and the best vegetarian option is with avocado and cheese (mushroom and cheese a close second). All served in double-wrapper corn tortillas. Beer and margaritas are on the menu, too.

Now this is a great taco place. Just a block off of U street it's a great place to stop for a bite before a show or while your drinking. It's feels incredibly authentic and the food is absolutely delicious. 3 tacos for $9 is about standard in DC and is far more worth it here. They use corn tortillas and are inherently gluten free. I tried the chicken, steak, and al pastor tacos. They were excellent and I wish I had ordered more. The guac is fresh made and variably spicy, depending on how you like it.  Their brick-and-mortar location is just a little house so it feels incredibly comfortable and is very inviting.  I'll certainly be going back in time for my next show at Black Cat if not sooner. I definitely recommend everyone.  tl;dr - delicious authentic tacos. Try the steak, chicken, al pastor, and guac. Very inviting and friendly staff. I will definitely go again.

The best tacos I've gotten from a food truck in the DC area. It's hard enough finding authentic Mexican tacos at a sit-down location around here, let alone a food truck. El Chilango fills that void.  They offer six kinds of tacos: carne asada, pollo, al pastor, chorizo, lengua, and mixto. We originally got 9 but they gave a free one, so we each ended up with 5 tacos. So nice of them! We got everything except pollo. The smell wafting from the truck was intoxicating. They handed two plates of tacos, topped with cilantro, limes, onions, radishes, and cucumbers. And you can add as much red or green sauce as you can handle.  All the tacos were delicious, but I thought their carne asada taco was especially good. All in all, authentic, tasty, cheap (only $2.50 each) tacos and great service. My usual preferred tacos come from Tacos El Costalilla and La Mexicana Bakery in Alexandria, but if I don't want to drive out that way, El Chilango is definitely an approved alternative.  CASH ONLY.

One of the worst tacos I have ever tried. The Al pastor looked like it was a stew! Gross. It was so bad my wife and I pretty much threw it away. The margarita tasted like the premix from cosco. Not worth it.Try harder my friends as this is no where near good.

The food was mediocre. I am mexican american and have been to mexico (guadalajara jalisco) plenty of times and have also been through texas and california particularly the san jose/bay area and KNOW what good tacos are supposed to taste like. I have been looking for traditional tacos that you taste anywhere remotely close to something you would find in mexico or california. If you are in the maryland dc or virginia area you should try Taqueria La Placita. By far the closest to a traditional taqueria that is not americanized at all. At Tacos El Chilango, I had the al pastor and the chorizo tacos. The chorizo tacos where not bad but not great either, the al pastor had to have been the worst ive ever had. First of all, in mexico the meat is cooked on a rod that spins in circles with heat on the back side so that the meat is cooked evenly as it spins with pinapples on top of the meat so that the juices cook into the meat. Here there where pineapple peices in the taco which it shouldnt have been and the meat was shredded it seemed like. Never had it like that before but maybe thats how they do it in Mexico City. Most reviews are positve but come from people who actually do not know what they are talking about or review something that a place is not known for. If tacos are what you specialize in then your great reviews should not be on the guacamole dip and chips. I would not go back here at all. Coming from somebody who pursued culinary arts, I would not advise this place to anybody looking for a good TAQUERIA this side of the border.

Heard about some good taquerias in DC and decided to give this place a shot. I'm from Texas and have had some great experiences with those establishments near the border, and this place delivers! Had the Tacos de Carnes today (al pastor, mixto, and chorizo) - great deal at $7.50 plus $1.50 for a can of coke. Great flavor with the meat, awesome authentic tortillas, and you gotta have the habanero salsa. Will come back when I'm around U street - probably after a Black Cat show sometime.
